<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1436,258,391]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,258,283]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The most distinctive feature of this species, although difficult to see and easily overlooked, is the presence on the lower half of the facial ridge of a row of minute white hairs, best observed against a dark background (
<figureCitation box="[301,370,330,355]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[340,1246,375,1280]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[340,1247,375,1280]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 3. Lateral view of head of Houghia fimbriata sp. nov. Arrow indicates the small decumbent hairs along the facial ridge." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287016/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[355,370,331,355]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Supporting character states are the orange base of the first flagellomere (also present in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macilenta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">H. macilenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
